Amazon NFT — European Fulfillment Network Analysis
Overview

This dataset models a multi-echelon European fulfillment network across a 4-month period (Sep–Dec 2024), combining operational, inventory, and customer demand data to analyze network efficiency and compare push vs. pull replenishment strategies.

Total Tables: 9
Total Records: 27,325
Time Coverage: 4 months
Scope: End-to-end supply chain (supplier → DC → IXD → FC → customer)
Data Model Structure

Upstream Supply

suppliers (10): Vendor master data (lead times, reliability)
purchase_orders (125): Replenishment orders into DCs

Network Infrastructure

nodes (24): All physical locations (DC, RDC, IXD, FC, NEXUS)

Product Layer

skus (250): Product catalogue with cost, weight, demand profile, velocity

Inventory & Flow

inventory (1,312): Current stock snapshot across nodes
transfers (2,860): Movements between nodes (core flow table)

Decision & Simulation Layer

replenishment_comparison (4,849): Push vs pull scenario modeling

Customer Demand

orders (16,615): Customer orders and fulfillment outcomes

Performance Monitoring

sla_performance (1,280): Transit time vs SLA tracking
Network Design

Node Types & Roles

1DC: Primary distribution center (bulk storage, daily replenishment)
RDC: Regional buffer (slow-moving inventory, weekly replenishment)
IXD: Cross-dock (sorting, no storage, continuous flow)
FC: Fulfillment center (pick, pack, ship)
NEXUS: Last-mile dispatch hub
Key Business Logic

1. Inventory Metrics

Capacity Utilization = units_on_hand / max_capacity
Stock Gap = units_on_hand - reorder_point
Holding Cost = units_on_hand × daily_storage_cost

2. Product Segmentation

Fast: Daily demand → highest priority
Medium: Weekly demand
Slow: Monthly demand

3. Demand Profiles

Flat | Winter Peak | Summer Peak | Event-Driven

4. SLA Targets

DC/RDC → IXD: ≤ 10 hrs
IXD → FC: ≤ 5 hrs
Core Analytical Use Cases
Network Flow Optimization:
Analyze transfer routes, costs, and bottlenecks
Inventory Efficiency:
Identify overstock, stockouts, and capacity issues
Push vs Pull Strategy Evaluation:
Compare cost, idle time, and stockout risk
Customer Fulfillment Performance:
Measure service levels and stockout impact
SLA & Delay Root Cause Analysis:
Track delays (e.g., customs, weather, capacity constraints)

Critical Notes
Inventory is a snapshot (not time-series)
Replenishment table is simulated (not historical decisions)
Orders include seasonality effects (e.g., Black Friday spikes)
Transfers are the primary source of truth for actual network movement
